 When one of these photons strikes a loosely bound electron that is initally
 at rest, energy and momentum are transferred from the photon to the electron.
 Due to this transfer of energy and momentum, the scattered x-ray photon
 has lower energy and therefore a larger wavelength.
 Note that another important characteristic of Compton scattering is that
 the phase of the scattered wave has no direct relationship to the phase
 of the incident beam, thus making this scattering incoherent and preventing
 interference effects.
